// JIT kernel: unary math functions in a hot loop via a direct libm C call.
//
// math.sqrt(x) compiles as GETTABUP(_ENV["math"]) -> SELF(math["sqrt"]) -> CALL.
// The recorder recognizes the SELF as a known strictly-unary libm math method
// and lowers the CALL to an SPTIR_FMATH: a direct C call to the libm function
// (sqrt/sin/cos/...), with the argument in XMM0 and the result read back from
// XMM0. A GUARD_CFUNC pins math["sqrt"] to the exact known C function (looked up
// at run time), so reassigning the method or the whole math table side-exits to
// the interpreter. The math library table is re-derived at record time from the
// stable _ENV upvalue (not the live R[B] register, which is overwritten by the
// call result inside the loop body). FMATH is not RA-safe, so these traces run
// with register allocation disabled; the trace body keeps the stack 8 (mod 16)
// so one `sub rsp,8` aligns for the call. Covers float args, an int arg (a TOFLT
// is inserted before the call), and several different math functions so multiple
// libm targets and the per-call guard are all exercised. Output is a transcendental
// sum, identical to the interpreter (the guards, not the prediction, are load-bearing).
list<float> fa = [0.25, 0.5, 1.0, 1.5, 2.0, 2.5, 3.0, 3.5];
list<int> ia = [1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64];
float s = 0.0;
for (int rep = 0, 3000) {
  for (int j = 0, 7) {
    s = s + math.sqrt(fa[j]) + math.sin(fa[j]) + math.cos(fa[j]) + math.sqrt(ia[j]);
  }
}
print(s);
